@Node "cs_trap" "installer.guide/cs_trap"

@Next "cs_onerror"
@Prev "cs_exit"
@Toc "Control Statements"

@{B}The `trap' statement
--------------------@{UB}

     (trap <trapflags> <statements>)

   Used for catching errors.  Works much like C `longjmp', i.e.  when an
error occurs, control is passed to the statement after `trap'.
`trapflags' determine which errors are trapped.  The trap statement
itself returns the error type or zero if no error occurred.  The current
error type values are:

     1 == user aborted

     2 == ran out of memory

     3 == error in script

     4 == DOS error (see `@ioerr' below)

     5 == bad parameter data


@EndNode


@Node "cs_onerror" "installer.guide/cs_onerror"

@Next "cs_trace"
@Prev "cs_trap"
@Toc "Control Statements"

@{B}The `onerror' statement
-----------------------@{UB}

     (onerror <statements>)

   When a fatal error occurs that was not trapped, a set of statements
can be called to clean-up after the script.  These statements are
logged in by using the onerror construct.  Note that onerror can be
used multiple times to allow context sensitive termination.


@EndNode


@Node "cs_trace" "installer.guide/cs_trace"

@Next "cs_retrace"
@Prev "cs_onerror"
@Toc "Control Statements"

@{B}The `trace' statement (V44)
---------------------------@{UB}

     (trace)

   The trace statement sets a backtrace position. A retrace will
continue on that position in the script. You can set as many backtrace
positions as you want.

   Example:

     (trace)
     (message "one trace is set")
     (trace)
     (message "a second trace is set")
     (retrace)

   This example will run until the (retrace) statement and continue
with the first (trace) statement (one trace is skipped and the previous
one is used).  This is an endless loop that will always present both
message pages to the user.


@EndNode


@Node "cs_retrace" "installer.guide/cs_retrace"

@Prev "cs_trace"
@Toc "Control Statements"

@{B}The `retrace' statement (V44)
-----------------------------@{UB}

     (retrace)

   The retrace initiates the backtrace mechanism. It skips the last
backtrace position and searchs for the previous one.

   Backtrace positions get lost if the script leaves a scope.

   Example:

     (trace)
     (message "now follows an if statement")
     (if (= 1 1)
         ((trace) (message "then"))
         (message "else")
     )
     (trace)
     (retrace)

   The script skips back to the first (trace) statement and not into
the "then" part of the if statement. So you will see the messages "now
follows..." and "then" again and again (until you abort the script).

   Note: If you use the backtrace mechanism via trace and retrace it is
very important to divide you installer script into two sections: First
ask the user all questions and retrive all data you need. Second do all
the action like copying files.

   In the first section you should allow the user to go back at every
command with user interaction. In the second section don't use the
"back" parameter in the copyfiles, copylib etc commands.

   The reason for this is very simple: All the actions from copyfile to
startup and tooltype cannot be inverted easily. It is very difficult to
replace a library with the older version again once you used copylib.

   For the same reason askdisk should not have a back parameter: if the
disk is already installed the operation is a no-op. So if you inserted
a trace statement before that askdisk you get an endless loop:

     (trace)
     (askdisk ... (back (retrace)))
     
     (trace)
     (message "Try to go back" (back (retrace)))

   If the disk is already inserted askdisk is a no-op and the the user
cannot go back before the first trace statement which leads to an
endless loop.  Currently there is no easy way to avoid this besides not
using "trace" and "back" for the askdisk function.

   The same is true for other statements that may not interact with the
user like copylib which is a no-op if the file to be copied has no
higher version number than the file at the destination. But as said
before these statements should not use the backtrace mechanism at all.


@EndNode


